            "@type": "dctypes:Text",
            "format": "text/html",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.XIX-XX.R9</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Set the darkness and vengeance against the New Testament</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-92ce470f-7fff-ca4a-5711-01d92ebce4a4\">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This thematic instruction indicates just how aware Dickens was of the opposition he set up between Amy and Mrs. Clennam. The chapter will make this Biblical opposition explicit when Mrs. Clennam describes her &ldquo;vengeance&rdquo; in Old Testament terms, and Little Dorrit responds with a reference to Christ. Mrs. Clennam describes herself as &ldquo;set&hellip; against evil&rdquo; and &ldquo;an instrument of severity against sin.&rdquo; Little Dorrit takes Mrs. Clennam&rsquo;s reference to &ldquo;the old days&rdquo; and transforms it: &ldquo;[L]et me implore you to remember later and better days. Be guided only by the healer of the sick, the raiser of the dead, the friend of all who were afflicted and forlorn&hellip; There is no vengeance and no infliction of suffering in His life, I am sure&rdquo; (LD 770).&nbsp;</p>"
